Ticket # INC0352668
Issue: User can’t access SharePoint website

Gather Information
•	Is the user receiving any errors or messages when trying to access SharePoint?
•	What browser is the user using?
•	Did the user try a different device?
•	Is the user able to access other programs?

Identify What Has Changed
•	Review the network to see if there have been any updates or security patches.

Create a Hypothesis
•	The user could be using an outdated browser.
•	User’s permissions may have changed.
•	Check SharePoint to see if there was an update to SharePoint’s server or if there is any ongoing maintenance.

Determine the Appropriate Fix
•	User should try clearing cache and cookies before accessing SharePoint.
•	Try accessing SharePoint from another network.
•	Check to see if the user’s rights need to be updated if they are receiving a permissions error.
•	Ask them to install a browser they do not have already and try with that.

Implement the Fix
•	If the issue is regarding the browser, clear cache and cookies or update the browser.
•	Troubleshoot network settings or escalate to network team if networking is the issue.
•	Update user rights if permissions are the issue.
•	Confirm with the user that they can access the SharePoint site.

Ensure Satisfaction
•	Confirm user has access to SharePoint.
•	Offer additional assistance if needed.

Document the Solution
•	Document information provided by the user, what has changed, hypothesis, and the fix.





Ticket # INC0354837
Issue: When I boot my desktop, I get a blue screen. The help desk upgraded my machine yesterday to Windows 10. What do I need to do? Please send someone to my desk. I'm on the 3rd floor at the main building.

Gather Information
•	Is the system displaying an error message?
•	At what point did the error occur during the installation process?
•	Did you confirm you were using the correct login credentials?
•	Did you make any changes to the system configuration?
•	Did you try to restart in safe mode?

Identify What Has Changed
•	The user’s system was updated to Windows 10, possibly causing changes within the prior existing drivers or software when it finished.

Create a Hypothesis
•	Drivers may be incompatible.
•	Installation may not have fully completed or corrupted during the installation process.
•	Previously downloaded programs may not be compatible with Windows 10.

Determine the Appropriate Fix
•	Use the settings app to clear the previous files, this will allow the system to re-download the upgrade bits.
•	Troubleshoot the errors with the “SetupDiag” tool which offers an optional download to diagnose and determine why the update or upgrade failed to apply.

Implement the Fix
•	Reboot system in Safe Mode.
•	Reinstall/Update drivers to ensure they are compatible with Windows 10.
•	Redownload the Windows 10 update.
•	Delete any programs that are conflicting with the Windows 10 update.
•	Confirm system has booted correctly.

Ensure Satisfaction
•	Verify the system reboots without the blue screen.
•	Check to see if the user is experiencing any other issues.

Document the Solution
•	Document information provided by the user, what has changed, hypothesis, and the fix.






